bib_record.title: KeV-region analysis of the neutron capture cross-section of 237Np

free_txt: ANNRI(BL04) beam line of MLF at J-PARC
Pulse-height weighting technique (PHWT) was applied.
Measurements with the carbon sample,
"Dummy replica sample", and "Blank (no sample) " were
used for back ground estimation. The relative neutron
spectrum was estimated using the boron sample.
The absolute neutron capture cross-section was
obtained by applying two normalization techniques.
In the first technique, the relative cross section
was normalized to the evaluated value in JENDL-4.0
at the first resonance.
In the second technique, the weighting function was
normalized using the Au thick sample at the saturated
first resonance.
Dead Time Correction was applied with a similar
method proposed by T. Katabuchi. (See. REL-REF)
Correction factors for self shielding and multiple
scattering were deduced using the Monte-Carlo
simulation code PHITS.
The NaI(Tl) spectrometer was used consisting
of two different sized NaI(Tl) detectors. The larger
detector: 330 mm (diam.) and 203 mm long, placed at
90 deg. with respect to the neutron beam. The smaller
detector: 203mm (diam.) and 203 mm long, placed at
125 deg. with respect to the neutron beam.
ANNRI(BL04) beam line of MLF at J-PARC
Spallation reaction in a mercury target
irradiated with 3-GeV protons. Produced neutrons were
slowed down in a supercritical para hydrogen
moderator (140 mm in diam., 120 mm in height) . The
proton beams were supplied at a repetition rate of 25
Hz and under a proton beam power of 400 kW with
"single-bunch mode".
The neutron spectrum was reconstructed using the 478
keV gamma-rays from gamma rays from 10B(n,alpha1) 7Li
reaction. The cross section values were taken from
JENDL-4.0.
Flight path length of 27.9 m.
Data
acquisition system and dead time correction.
Data from the same experiment in the low energy region
227 mg of NpO2 powder (5MBq) mixed with 625 mg of
metal Al powder at the room temperature. Sample
powder was pressed into a pellet shape with a
diameter 20 mm, and sealed in an Al case (outer
diameter of 30 mm and 0.4 mm thick walls).
A B4C sample containing enriched 10B up to 90% with a
diameter of 10 mm and a thickness of 0.5 mm was used
for neutron spectrum measurement.
A natural carbon sample (93.0 mg/cm2, 10 mm in diam.)
was used as neutron scatterer to subtract background.
An Au thick foil sample was used for normalization.
